## 15. gRPC API

Create `proto/hostagent.proto`:

```proto
syntax = "proto3";

package pgmaker.hostagent.v1;

service HostAgentService {
  rpc StreamMetrics(stream AgentControl) returns (stream MetricEnvelope);
  rpc SetSamplingConfig(SamplingConfig) returns (SamplingAck);
  rpc GetSnapshot(SnapshotRequest) returns (MetricEnvelope);
  rpc GetHealth(HealthRequest) returns (MetricEnvelope);
}

message AgentControl {
  string request_id = 1;
  oneof command {
    SamplingConfig sampling_config = 2;
    SnapshotRequest snapshot_request = 3;
    RefreshRequest refresh_request = 4;
    Ping ping = 5;
  }
}

message SamplingConfig {
  string profile = 1; // normal, pressure, incident, custom
  uint32 ttl_seconds = 2;
  uint32 heartbeat_seconds = 3;
  uint32 cpu_seconds = 4;
  uint32 memory_seconds = 5;
  uint32 swap_seconds = 6;
  uint32 io_seconds = 7;
  uint32 mounts_seconds = 8;
  uint32 disk_seconds = 9;
  uint32 lvm_seconds = 10;
  uint32 top_seconds = 11;
  uint32 top_process_count = 12;
}

message SnapshotRequest {
  bool include_static = 1;
  bool include_top = 2;
  bool force_refresh = 3;
}

message RefreshRequest {
  repeated string categories = 1; // cpu, memory, swap, disk, io, mounts, lvm, top, static
}

message Ping {
  string message = 1;
}

message SamplingAck {
  string status = 1;
  string active_profile = 2;
  string message = 3;
}

message HealthRequest {}

message MetricEnvelope {
  string host = 1;
  string agent_version = 2;
  string collected_at = 3;
  string category = 4; // snapshot, cpu, memory, io, top, health, etc.
  string json = 5;     // JSON payload for easy Node.js ingestion
  repeated string warnings = 6;
}
```

Important: use `json` as a string inside the protobuf envelope initially. This keeps Node.js integration simple and avoids recreating every nested structure twice. Later, we can replace JSON string with strongly typed protobuf messages.

## 16. gRPC dynamic sampling behavior

The aggregator must be able to send this over the stream:

```json
{
  "profile": "pressure",
  "ttl_seconds": 300,
  "cpu_seconds": 2,
  "memory_seconds": 2,
  "io_seconds": 2,
  "top_seconds": 5,
  "top_process_count": 50
}
```

Expected behavior:

1. Agent updates active sampling config in memory.
2. Agent immediately refreshes selected categories.
3. Agent sends an ack.
4. Agent keeps pressure sampling for `ttl_seconds`.
5. After TTL expires, agent returns to normal profile unless a newer config exists.

Also support permanent profile change through HTTP debug endpoint.

## 17. Scheduler design

Implement a background scheduler that updates cached data.

```text
normal profile:
  CPU every 10s
  Memory every 10s
  IO every 10s
  Top every 30s
  Mounts every 60s
  Disk every 300s
  LVM every 300s
  Static every 3600s

pressure profile:
  CPU every 2s
  Memory every 2s
  IO every 2s
  Top every 5s
```

Use independent category workers, not one big loop.

Each worker:

1. Waits for interval.
2. Collects metric.
3. Updates shared state.
4. Records collection duration and errors.
5. Sleeps again.

Use `tokio::select!` so workers can react to config changes.

